\/span><\/li><\/ul><\/li><li class=\"li\">Modal verbs are followed by the infinitive of another verb without <span class=\"eb\">to<\/span>. The exceptions are <span class=\"eb\">ought to<\/span>, <span class=\"eb\">have to<\/span> and <span class=\"eb\">used to<\/span>:<ul class=\"eg\"><li><span class=\"unx\">You must find a job.<\/span><\/li><li><span class=\"unx\">You ought to stop smoking.<\/span><\/li><li><span class=\"unx\">I used to smoke but I gave up two years ago.<\/span><\/li><\/ul><\/li><li class=\"li\">Questions are formed without <span class=\"eb\">do<\/span>\/<span class=\"eb\">does<\/span> in the present, or <span class=\"eb\">did<\/span> in the past:<ul class=\"eg\"><li><span class=\"unx\">Can I invite Mary?<\/span><\/li><li><span class=\"unx\">Should I have invited Mary?<\/span><\/li><\/ul><\/li><li class=\"li\">Negative sentences are formed with <span class=\"eb\">not<\/span> or the short form <span class=\"eb\">-n\u2019t<\/span> and do not use <span class=\"eb\">do<\/span>\/<span class=\"eb\">does<\/span> or <span class=\"eb\">did<\/span>.<\/li><\/ul><span class=\"p\">You will find more help with how to use modal verbs at the dictionary entries for each verb.<\/span><\/span><\/div>  <\/li><div class=\"idioms\"><h2 class=\"h2\">Idioms<\/h2><div class=\"d1\"><span class=\"idm-g\"><h3 class=\"idioms_h2\">don\u2019t you dare!<\/h3><li class=\"sense\"><span class=\"sensetop\"><span class=\"labels\">(informal)<\/span><\/span> <span class=\"def\">used to tell somebody strongly not to do something<\/span><ul class=\"eg\"><li><span class=\"x\">\u2018I'll tell her about it.\u2019 \u2018Don't you dare!\u2019<\/span><\/li><li><span class=\"x\">Don't you dare say anything to anybody.<\/span><\/li><\/ul> <\/li><\/span><span class=\"idm-g\"><h3 class=\"idioms_h2\">how dare you, etc.<\/h3><li class=\"sense\"><span class=\"sensetop\"><span class=\"def\">used to show that you are angry about something that somebody has done<\/span><\/span><ul class=\"eg\"><li><span